questions.explanation:
The `-o` flag stands for "output" and tells the compiler what to name the resulting executable. Without it, the compiler defaults to producing a file called `a.out` on Linux/macOS. So `g++ -o myapp main.cpp` compiles `main.cpp` and produces an executable named `myapp`.

Common flags to know:
```cpp
// g++ -o myapp main.cpp   → output named 'myapp'
// g++ main.cpp            → output defaults to 'a.out'
// g++ -Wall main.cpp      → enable all warnings
```

