What is the output?
```cpp
int x = 3, y = 4;
if (x > 2 && y < 3) std::cout << "A";
else if (x > 2 && y > 3) std::cout << "B";
else std::cout << "C";
```

What is the output?
```cpp
void foo() { int x = 5; }
int main() { std::cout << x; }
```

What is the output?
```cpp
void addTwo(int x) { x = x + 2; }
int main() {
    int n = 5;
    addTwo(n);
    std::cout << n;
}
```

questions.explanation:
The function `addTwo` takes its parameter **by value** — it receives a copy of `n`, not the original. Modifying the copy inside the function has no effect on `n` in `main()`, so `n` remains `5`.

To actually modify the caller's variable, pass by reference using `&`:
```cpp
void addTwo(int& x) { x = x + 2; }
// now addTwo(n) would change n to 7
```

