questions.explanation:
Local variables have **block scope** — they are only visible within the `{}` block where they are declared. When the function returns, local variables are automatically destroyed (their memory on the stack is reclaimed). Option B is a common misconception: called functions do **not** inherit access to the caller's local variables. Each function has its own independent scope.

```cpp
void callee() { /* cannot access caller's variables */ }
void caller() {
    int x = 5;   // x only visible here
    callee();    // callee cannot see x
}
```

