questions.explanation:
Dereferencing a `nullptr` is **undefined behavior**. On most systems this causes a **segmentation fault** (crash) because address `0` is not mapped to valid memory. The compiler does not catch this at compile time — it's a runtime error.

Always check before dereferencing:
```cpp
if (p != nullptr) {
    std::cout << *p;
} else {
    std::cout << "pointer is null";
}
```

