questions.explanation:
Every time a function is called, a **stack frame** is pushed onto the call stack (containing local variables, return address, etc.). If a function calls itself indefinitely with no base case to stop the recursion, stack frames accumulate without ever being popped. Eventually the stack memory is exhausted, causing a **stack overflow**.

```cpp
void infinite() { infinite(); } // never stops → stack overflow
void safe(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;  // base case stops recursion
    safe(n - 1);
}
```

Option A (`new int[100000]`) allocates on the **heap**, not the stack. Option C (double `delete`) is undefined behavior but not a stack overflow.

